explanation.en:
Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) is a very common condition that usually manifests with heartburn, regurgitation, and dysphagia. However, patients can have extraesophageal symptoms (eg, nocturnal cough, hoarseness) in the absence of heartburn ("silent GERD").

Gastroesophageal junction incompetence is the primary pathophysiologic mechanism responsible for GERD. This incompetence is most commonly caused by excessive relaxation of the lower esophageal sphincter, resulting in the reflux of acidic gastric contents back into the esophagus. Irritation of the esophageal mucosa leads to an inflammatory reaction with mucosal erythema and edema; erosions/ulcerations may develop in severe cases. Characteristic histologic findings include basal zone hyperplasia, elongation of the lamina propria papillae, and scattered eosinophils and neutrophils. {{exhibit_1}}

(Choice A) Absent esophageal peristaltic movements can be seen with achalasia and systemic sclerosis. The distinctive histopathologic findings of systemic sclerosis involving the esophagus include atrophy of the muscularis with collagenous fibrosis.

(Choice B) Eosinophilic esophagitis is an immune/antigen-mediated disease that typically presents with dysphagia and food impaction in atopic adults. It is characterized histologically by numerous superficially located intraepithelial eosinophils, which can help differentiate it from reflux esophagitis.

(Choice D) Candida albicans is the most common cause of infectious esophagitis in HIV and immunocompromised patients. Endoscopy typically shows white plaques on an erythematous mucosa, and light microscopy demonstrates pseudohyphae and budding spores embedded in necrotic debris. {{exhibit_2}}

(Choice E) Herpes simplex virus (HSV) and cytomegalovirus (CMV) are other common causes of infectious esophagitis in immunocompromised patients. HSV usually shows punched-out ulcers on endoscopy with eosinophilic nuclear inclusions on biopsy. In contrast, CMV produces shallow/linear ulcers with nuclear/cytoplasmic viral inclusions. {{exhibit_3}}

(Choice F) Pill-induced esophagitis is commonly seen with tetracycline antibiotics, potassium chloride, and bisphosphonates. Metformin and enalapril do not cause esophagitis. {{exhibit_4}}

Educational objective:
Gastroesophageal reflux disease is caused primarily by gastroesophageal junction incompetence and can be associated with extraesophageal symptoms (eg, nocturnal cough) in the absence of heartburn ("silent GERD"). Acidic gastric contents irritate the esophageal mucosa, leading to characteristic histologic findings that include basal zone hyperplasia, elongation of the lamina propria papillae, and scattered eosinophils. {{exhibit_5}} {{exhibit_6}}

explanation.zh:
胃食管反流病 (GERD) 是一种非常常见的疾病，通常表现为烧心、反流和吞咽困难。然而，患者可能在没有烧心的情况下出现食管外症状（例如，夜间咳嗽、声音嘶哑）（“无声 GERD”）。

胃食管连接处功能不全是导致 GERD 的主要病理生理学机制。这种功能不全最常见的原因是食管下括约肌过度松弛，导致酸性胃内容物反流回食管。食管粘膜受到刺激会导致炎症反应，出现粘膜红斑和水肿；严重情况下可能发展为糜烂/溃疡。特征性组织学发现包括基底区增生、固有层乳头增生以及散在的嗜酸性粒细胞和中性粒细胞。 {{exhibit_1}}

(选项 A) 食管蠕动缺失可见于贲门失弛缓症和系统性硬化症。系统性硬化症累及食管的特征性组织病理学发现包括肌层萎缩伴有胶原纤维化。

(选项 B) 嗜酸性粒细胞性食管炎是一种免疫/抗原介导的疾病，通常表现为吞咽困难和食物嵌塞，常见于特应性成人。其组织学特征是表层存在大量上皮内嗜酸性粒细胞，这有助于将其与反流性食管炎区分开来。

(选项 D) 白色念珠菌是 HIV 和免疫功能低下患者感染性食管炎的最常见原因。内镜检查通常显示在红斑粘膜上有白色斑块，光镜下显示假菌丝和芽孢嵌入坏死碎屑中。{{exhibit_2}}

(选项 E) 单纯疱疹病毒 (HSV) 和巨细胞病毒 (CMV) 是免疫功能低下患者感染性食管炎的其他常见原因。HSV 通常在内镜检查中显示穿凿样溃疡，活检显示嗜酸性核内包涵体。相比之下，CMV 产生浅表/线状溃疡，并伴有核/胞质内病毒包涵体。 {{exhibit_3}}

(选项 F) 药物引起的食管炎通常见于四环素类抗生素、氯化钾和双膦酸盐。二甲双胍和依那普利不会引起食管炎。{{exhibit_4}}

教育目标：
胃食管反流病主要由胃食管连接处功能不全引起，并且在没有烧心的情况下可能与食管外症状（例如，夜间咳嗽）相关（“无声 GERD”）。酸性胃内容物刺激食管粘膜，导致特征性组织学发现，包括基底区增生、固有层乳头增生和散在的嗜酸性粒细胞。{{exhibit_5}} {{exhibit_6}}
